review_blob: Pours a nice gold color with a quickly dissipating finger of head.  Aroma is slightly sweet and malty with a hint of hops.  Flavor is clean and slightly hoppy, reminded me slightly of a good pilsner with a bit more body.  Very well-rounded.
Deep red pour with a finger of off-white head.  Very bready/malty aroma and taste; some smoke notes.  Medium, slightly creamy mouthfeel.

Pours a dark amber with a small head.  Aroma is of malts and nutty with some caramel tones.  Taste is very bready and sweet with a spicy aftertaste.  Mouthfeel is average and overall a very drinkable, good tasting Oktoberfest.

Widget can pours with great cascading effect and a copper color.  Aroma is faint but it is slightly malty.  Taste is malty with slight bitterness and it is very easily drunk.  Texture is nice due to the nitrogen widget.  Great session beer.

On tap.  Had an amber color with little head.  Very malty aroma.  Taste was malty with a slight bit of hops.  Very thin mouthfeel for an ale, but impressive for and AB product.  I would order it if I had nothing else though I will not go out of my way to drink it a lot.

Can poured into pint glass with a thick head that lasts a while.  Has a golden color and aroma that is surprisingly mildly fruity.  Taste is slightly sweet and malty.  Very little hop bitterness.  Mouthfeel is nice due to the nitrogen widget.  Overall, a good-tasting session beer.

Living in Athens, this has become one of my recent staples.  Pours a nice amber color with a slight aroma of floral hops.  Flavor is strong, the rye comes out before being overtaken by a strong, but not overpowering hop taste.  Overall a very well-balanced beer.

Bottle.  Pours a golden color and has a fruity aroma.  Tasted much like an overhopped wheat beer; I feel some of the extra emphasis on hops and high alcohol overpowered the fruit tastes one would expect from a wheat beer.  Mouthfeel is strangely sticky.  Not an awful brew, but I expected better from Terrapin.
On tap at Terrapin Brewery.  Has a medium brown color with a malty aroma.  Taste is mostly of hops, though some of the extra roasted characters in the malt came through.  An impressive beer.

On tap at Terrapin Brewery.  Has a medium amber color with a slight hop aroma.  Taste is relatively simple with some citrus notes, but not simple in a bad way.  Beer does feel a little bit thin, but for this style, I did not mind.

On tap at Terrapin brewery.  A good offering, though not my favorite from Terrapin.  Being a fan of Pilsners in general, I felt for once that Terrapin overhopped the beer this time and changed the profile too far away from being a Pilsner.  With that said, I found the sweet taste up front followed by the strong hops to be an interesting blend of tastes.

My first Scottish Ale, poured from a bottle, has a deep amber color with a medium head.  Slight smoke aroma with a heavy malt smell.  Taste is malty with an interesting spiciness.  Has a slightly sweet finish.  Not too thick on the body.

Bottle.  Pours black with slight head.  Aroma of coffee and chocolate.  Nice, thick body yet smooth.  Alcohol is noticeable but not overpowering, and the sweet, highly roasted malts take control of the taste.  An amazing offering.
On draught; Has a nice nutty aroma with coffee/chocolate taste.  Good overall impression.
UPDATED: DEC 21, 2008

Bottle Poured into a standard pint glass with a faint copper color and thin head.  Aroma is very spicy and hoppy with a faint amount of malt aroma.  Taste is slightly malty and fruity up front with a heavy hop finish.  However, it was not overly bitter nor the most bitter IPA Ive had.  Mouthfeel is average with an average amount of carbonation and some alcohol notes.  Overall I thought this was a good IPA, especially if you are making the transition from less hoppy styles.

Pours a deep golden amber color with a nice finger of white head.  Aroma is citrusy and has some hop notes.  Flavor is medium malt up front with a nice hop finish.  Has just the right amount of bitterness to me.  Body isnt too thin, but not extremely thick or heavy and has a nice, balanced carbonation.  A very refreshing beer with some body and bite to it.  Another great offering from Brooklyn (they now have me hooked).

Pours a medium amber with a small, short-lasting head that dissipates to a nice lacing.  Aroma is balanced between yeast, malts and hops, but is very mild overall.  Taste is fairly hoppy for the style with some hints of the malt character behind it.  Mouthfeel is still on the watery side, but it doesnt detract from the overall experience.  Another excellent, drinkable offering from the Brooklyn Brewery.

Pours a nice, clear straw color with a finger of head that becomes nice lacing when it dissipates.  Nose is slightly spicy of hops.  There is a mild sweetness up front followed by a satisfying bitterness that youd expect out of a pilsner.  Body is pretty thin, but thats acceptable fo thos type of beer.  It is a typical pilsner with more flavor and another strong offering from the folks at Brooklyn.

Pours a dark brown with a thick tan head.  Aroma is very malty and nutty.  Taste is of roasted malts and coffee up front with slight bitterness towards the back.  The carbonation is alright, but nowhere near the mouthfeel of regular Guinness on a nitrogen tab.  Still a good and decently drinkable beer.

Pours a medium straw color into a pint glass.  With a small head that becomes a decent amount of lacing.  Aroma is grassy and slightly hoppy.  Taste is slightly malty sweet up front and slightly hoppy as it finishes.  Overall a decent, drinkable brew.

Poured a dark mahogany brown into a pint glass with a finger of head that dissipated into some decent lacing.  Aroma was nutty and also had some nice roasted malt scent.  Taste was malty and nutty with some chocolate and coffee overtones.  A nice amount of hops (more than something like a Newcastle for comparisons sake) finished an excellent, drinkable brew.

Pours a pale gold/deep straw color with a cloudiness thats to be expected of the style.  Very fruity smell with some of the banana aroma one can expect with a Weizen.  Taste is very yeasty and slightly fruity/sweet.  Mouthfeel is a nice consistency with a tendency towards the thin side with a good level of carbonation.  Overall a nice find and extremely drinkable, well-rounded beer.

Ive heard a lot about Brooklyn Brewerys offerings, so I bought a few singles today; this was my first I tried.  Pours a clear, medium gold with slight head.  Aroma is bready with some definite citrus notes thrown in there.  Taste is bready with some citrus up front with a surprising amount of hops towards the back for a Golden Ale, though the flavor is quite nice.  Mouthfeel is a little thin, but this is a tasty, extremely drinkable beer.

Poured 12 oz. bottle into Pint glass.

Color was a deep amber; finger of head that rapidly dissipated.  Aroma was very malty, as was the taste.  I could sense some caramel notes, and there were just enough hops to finish without too much bitterness.  Mouthfeel was good -- It had the right amount of carbonation.  Overall a very good Oktoberfest type of beer.

Dark gold pour into a pint glass; finger of head that lasted about a minute; good amount of lacing.  Aroma was slightly of floral hops.  Taste was ever so slightly sweet up front and finished with a mild bitter hop flavor.  Mouthfeel was very good, had the right amount of carbonation, and didnt leave any lingering aftertaste.  Overall, a very drinkable beer with a very good overall flavor.

Poured pale golden color into a pint glass; very little head which quickly dissipated.  Very mild cereal aroma.  Taste is very mildly sweet and malty at the front with a very slight hoppy finish.  Overall, though, there wasnt a very strong flavor presence throughout.  Still, though, I would not say this was a terrible beer, just average.  Mouthfeel was decent, and this is very drinkable.

Pours an extremely pale straw yellow.  No head retention.  Almost imperceptible aroma.  Taste was just as imperceptible; I tasted much more can than anything else.  Absolutely never let this beer warm up before you finish it or you will not finish it.  Almost not worth the low cost a case of these will cost you.

Poured a golden color with a finger of head that lasted a little over a minute.  Some lacing that remained most of the glass and pretty active carbonation.  Had a slightly bitter first taste while there was little aftertaste lingering after I swallowed.  Im usually not a fan of the pale lager style, but this seemed to be a pale lager with a lot better of an overall taste than anything else in the genre Ive tried.  An extremely drinkable beer to boot.

Poured a dark brown with a medium dark head.  Aroma was of slight roasted malts.  The flavor was acceptable, though not as strong as I had hoped.  There was some roasted maltiness in the flavor, but nothing overall stood out to me.  Had a clean, refreshing finish, but I was left wanting a little more.  This wasnt a bad beer, but there are much better dunkels out there.

Though I am usually not a fan of lighter beers or lagers in general, this created quite the positive impression on me.  Overall, I found it similar to Pilsner Urquell, though I felt it had a more subtle flavor overall.  Poured a pale, clear golden color with a finger of head.  Has a spicy, hoppy aroma, but nothing too strong.  Slight malty flavor at the front gives way to a nice, sharp hop flavor towards the back of the tongue.  Leaves little aftertaste.  A very nice summer beer much like Urquell.  The Czechs have impressed me again.

Poured from a bottle into a pint glass.

Has a slightly fruity, bready aroma and a medium head that dissipated relatively quickly.  An opaque, pale yellow from the fact it is unfiltered.  Had a sweet, bready taste, with just enough of a hint of citrus flavoring.  Finishes very cleanly; it had very little hop bitterness, though I dont expect this kind of beer to be very hoppy.  Extremely drinkable beer overall.

A nice, accessible Pale Ale.  Nice, Amber color poured into a pint glass from a 12 oz. bottle.  Some sweetness up front with a pleasing, hoppy bitterness in the back.  Smooth mouthfeel with a fairly low amount of carbonation.  Head retention is decent when properly poured; some nutty aroma, though nothing too strong.  A very drinkable and likable beer overall.

This was my first Dunkel I tried, having previously had Warsteiners Premium Verum.  The aroma was slight and of roasted malts.  When I drank this at home, it was straight out of the bottle, so I have little input on the appearance.  I liked the overall flavor.  It was mostly of roasted malts and a slight coffee.  However, I was expecting a slightly stronger roasted taste.  Nothing was wrong with the taste, though.  The texture was very smooth and drinkable, though a bit watery.  Overall an enjoyable beer but nothing spectacular.

This was a decent beer; nothing special, though.  Could not discern a strong aroma.  Bottle poured golden into a glass and left a tiny head that dissipated within a minute.  More of an overall bitter taste than I expected, but still a decent, light-bodied, drinkable beer.

The thing I most remember about this beer is that it had one of the most memorable aromas that jumped out at me as soon as I opened the bottle.  It was crisp and fairly strong, but not overpowering.  The appearance wasnt all too impressive to me -- yellow with a head that dissipated within a minute or two.  Flavor was good for a light beer as this, especially since I am a fan of the darker beers.  There was enough of a hoppy taste to tell you are drinking a good beer, but not so much hops as to overpower the taste.  Overall a well-balanced taste.  The texture was a bit thin but smooth.  Overall one of my favorite beers for chilling on the deck during the summer.

I tried this on tap at the A-B hospitality room at Sea World Orlando.  Given my previous experience with A-B products, I was leery of trying this, but since it was free I gave it a shot.  I have to say, I was impresses that there is an A-B product Id have again.  The appearance was a nice, solid black with a reasonably impressive head that lasted for most of the glass.  The smell seemed to be quite muted -- There wasnt much happening there besides some mild roasted smells.  I was impressed with the flavor, which had some chocolate and coffee taste to it.  The beer had a somewhat creamy texture with the head and carbonation, but overall it was a bit light for my tastes.  Still, I would rate this as perhaps the best A-B product Ive tried; maybe an upper middle class of beers Ive had.  If I had the choice, Id still order a Guinness over this, but I would drink it again.
